ndance of extant literature, the world continues to face leadership predicaments. Given the global crises mankind has been recently exposed to, which include the financial crisis of 2008 as well as the COVID-19 pandemic, further exploration of leadership concepts seems warranted. This edited book aims at introducing the concept of Balanced Leadership from an Islamic perspective. Drawing on both leadership and Islamic studies, the book synchronizes between secular and religious knowledge domains whilst introducing the notion of balance to mainstream leadership literature. The conceptualizations presented in the book serve to dissect the leadership literature, present historical and philosophical accounts of the balanced leadership concept and infuse that with Islamic theology. The book is useful for practitioners interested in leadership studies as well as scholars and researchers aiming at extending the leadership literature.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aLeadershipxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aLeadership. 4aBalanced Leadership. 4aFührung. 4aIslam. 4aLeadership. 4aReligion. 4aSpiritualität. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  aBalanced leadership.  aIslam.  aleadership.  areligion.  aspirituality.1 aAbdelrahman Farrag, Dalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbdelzaher, Dina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmin, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmin, Ahmed, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaykal, Elif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarrag, Menatallah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Odessy, Dina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula